chatgpt_double_star.new_statement: Government should ensure every resident can get essential care—primary, preventive, mental-health, and catastrophic coverage—without facing medical bankruptcy, while leaving room for people to choose among competing plans and providers. The public role should focus on setting clear minimum benefits, enforcing fair rules and transparency, and using its purchasing power to curb excessive prices and reduce administrative waste. States and local communities should have flexibility to deliver coverage through a mix of public programs and regulated private options, with performance measures so taxpayers and patients can see what works.

chatgpt_double_star_rankings.new_statement: Government should guarantee a reliable, affordable baseline of healthcare—covering preventive, mental-health, and catastrophic care—so no one faces medical bankruptcy or delayed treatment. That guarantee should be delivered with transparent pricing, clear quality standards, and streamlined administration to reduce waste and control costs. Use phased, accountable reforms that preserve patient choice and encourage innovation by partnering with private providers, employers, and local community and faith-based clinics, while allowing local flexibility to meet diverse needs.

chatgpt_double_star_personas.new_statement: Government should ensure every American can access a basic, affordable level of healthcare—especially preventive care, mental health support, and protection from catastrophic medical bills—so families can work and retire with dignity. That guarantee should come with clear limits and strong accountability: transparent prices, reduced bureaucracy, anti-fraud enforcement, and outcome-based standards to protect taxpayers. Preserve patient choice by partnering with private providers, employers, and local community and faith-based clinics, and phase reforms in so states and communities can adapt while keeping costs under control.
